What is AWS?

AWS (Amazon Web Services) is a cloud computing platform that provides over 200 services for building and managing applications.

AWS stands for:

Amazon Web Services

It is a cloud platform developed by Amazon.

AWS provides more than 200 cloud services.

Some popular services:

EC2
S3
IAM
VPC
RDS
Lambda
EKS
ECS
CloudWatch
Route53
Why Do Companies Use AWS?

Suppose Flipkart gets huge traffic during Diwali.

Instead of buying 1000 servers,

They simply launch more EC2 instances.

After Diwali,

they stop those instances.

They pay only for the days they used them.

Advantages of AWS
1. Pay as You Go

Pay only for what you use.

Example:

Renting a bike.

You pay only for the hours you ride it.

2. Highly Available

AWS has data centers around the world.

If one server fails,

another server continues serving users.

3. Scalable

Need more servers?

Launch them in minutes.

Need fewer servers?

Stop them.

4. Secure

AWS provides:

IAM
Security Groups
Encryption
Firewalls
Monitoring
5. Global

AWS is available in many countries.

Users connect to the nearest AWS data center.

Types of Cloud
1. Public Cloud

Owned by a cloud provider.

Example:

AWS
Azure
Google Cloud

Anyone can create an account.

2. Private Cloud

Owned by a single company.

Example:

A bank runs its own cloud inside its own data center.

Only employees can use it.

3. Hybrid Cloud

Combination of:

Public Cloud
Private Cloud

Example:

Customer data stays in the private cloud.

Web application runs on AWS.

Cloud Service Models
1. IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)

AWS provides:

Virtual Machines
Storage
Network

You manage:

OS
Applications
Software

Example:

EC2

2. PaaS (Platform as a Service)

AWS manages:

Servers
OS
Runtime

You only deploy your application.

Example:

Elastic Beanstalk

3. SaaS (Software as a Service)

Everything is managed by the provider.

Examples:

Gmail
Zoom
Microsoft 365

You simply use the application.
